\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The 70th\'a0annual\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.vogue.com/slideshow/met-gala-red-carpet-live-celebrity-fashion"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Met Gala}}\'a0once again exceeded expectations for over-the-top fashion, spectacle, and pageantry. The theme of this year\'92s ball was \'93Heavenly Bodies,\'94 with individual looks referencing papal garb, clerical vestments, saintly halos, angels, and icons.\
\
Last week, the companion exhibition,\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.metmuseum.org/exhibitions/listings/2018/heavenly-bodies"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3\i \cf4 \strokec4 Heavenly Bodies: Fashion and the Catholic Imagination}},\'a0opened to the public, showcasing a collection high-fashion inspired by Christian clothing, art, and architecture, alongside ecclesiastical vestments and accessories on loan from the Vatican. The common thread that ties together all the of these items is the elaborate ornamentation, meticulous fabrication, and lavish expense of the one-of-a-kind garments for which the Metropolitan Museum\'92s Costume Institute has come to be known.\
Although many\'a0\cf4 \strokec4 drooled over the red carpet looks\cf2 \strokec2 \'a0and are\'a0\cf4 \strokec4 awestruck by the exhibition\cf2 \strokec2 , some are complaining about what they see as the tastelessness \'97 and even offensiveness \'97 of the theme. Piers Morgan, for instance,\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-5703953/PIERS-MORGAN-Met-Islam-Jewish-themed-hell-break-loose-disrespect-religion.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 criticized the Met}}\'a0for making light of a religion held dear by many.\
As a historian of early Christianity with a specialty in religious dress, I think that Christians of the past would praise the Met organizers, curators, and designers for highlighting the role dress has played in the history of Christianity, while \'97 along with contemporary religious critics \'97 snubbing the Met for particular choices that indeed would have offended their religious sensibilities.\
\
On the one hand, early Christians would agree with the Met exhibition and gala organizers about the importance of dress as a primary mode through which individuals have long expressed their religious identity, commitment, and piety. Across early Christian sources, moments of conversion or of taking monastic vows were regularly marked by dramatic changes in garb that visibly signaled one\'92s new identity as a person of faith. In the words of\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf206.v.CXXX.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 4th\'965th\'a0century Christian writer Jerome}}, one\'92s appearance \'93put on display who one really was.\'94\
\
On the other hand, the particular form and pageantry of the garments on display at the Gala and the exhibition deviate markedly from those through which early Christians communicated their religiosity. First and foremost, early Christians dressed\'a0
