\f2\i0 . In an effort to express disdain for worldly luxury and attachments, and to live rather in anticipation of the world to come, they forsook ornamentation, fineries, and elaborately decorated or dyed garments, and rather donned the plain and simple clothing of the poor. Fourth\'a0century Christian Demetrias, for instance, was\'a0\cf4 \strokec4 reported\cf2 \strokec2 \'a0to have cast aside her \'93valuable necklaces, costly pearls, and sparkling gems\'94 in favor of a \'93cheap tunic, which she covered over with an even cheaper cloak.\'94 Early Christians would thus find the pomp and circumstance of the Met looks unthinkable within the parameters of their standards of religious piety.\
