\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec5 Last week, an early medieval burial site\'97since characterized as one of the most significant ever excavated in the UK\'97was\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.theguardian.com/science/2022/dec/06/medieval-female-burial-site-found-near-harpole-is-most-significant-ever-discovered-in-uk"}}{\fldrslt \ul discovered}}. Buried alongside its inhabitant from the Middle Ages was an intricate necklace of striking craftsmanship and complexity, made of wrought gold, garnets, and other semi-precious stones. It looked like something the popular jewelry brand\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://mondo-mondo.com/"}}{\fldrslt \ul Mondo Mondo}}\'a0might make. I\'92ve been taking note of a rising design trend that spans the realms of jewelry, fashion, and art. If you ask me, a major shift is afoot, and it appears to be taking us down an enchanting path, one far away from the Nickelodeon-ified postmodern and Peeps colored palettes that somehow managed to curdle the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/ultrafragola-mirror-dupes-impact"}}{\fldrslt \ul Ultrafragola}}\'a0in all its glory. (I won\'92t say good riddance, but I dare declare I\'92m ready to move on.)\
\
While I\'92ve never particularly wanted a\'a0canopy bed, lately I can\'92t help but wonder if I might sleep more soundly, wake more peacefully, and make love more ravishingly beneath sloping damasks and tousled in sumptuous silks. Blame the change of seasons if you must, but I chalk it up to more than just a brisk breeze. Whereas\'a0cottagecore\'97an undeniable reigning trend of the pandemic era\'97might have pointed to our collective longing for cozy and pastoral vibes, the emergence of this new aesthetic points to a tougher, more dramatic, and even mystical turn.\'a0\
\
The medieval era, often referred to as the Middle Ages or the Dark Ages, is bracketed between the fall of Rome in the fourth century through the beginning of the Renaissance in the early 16th century, a dizzying sprawl of time. To make matters even more expansive, it\'92s a particularly permeable period and genre within our collective imagination thanks to fantasy films and mythical tales. Where real medieval history ends and medieval myth begins can be hard for the average pleb to pin down. This intermingling impacts the way we experience and process a so-called medieval aesthetic. It might just be one of the few visual languages that someone without a background in art history can point out. (Suspending strict academic definitions, it\'92s a bit of a \'93you know it when you see it\'94 kind of thing.)\'a0\
\
Larisa Grollemond, a curator in the Manuscripts Department at the Getty Museum who recently \'a0contributed to an exhibit called\'a0\'93{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.getty.edu/art/exhibitions/fantasy/"}}{\fldrslt \ul The Fantasy of the Middle Ages}},\'94 notes that Medievalisms\'97the remixing of aspects of medieval art, architecture, and literature\'97are \'93a staple of our collective cultural knowledge.\'94 Thanks to representations of the period in film, television, video games, and a huge variety of other media, this world is \'93easy to reach for\'94 when we\'92re hungry for a new aesthetic. Within the collectible design space, a growing class of contemporary designers appears to be gravitating toward this world too, creating work that points to a longing for rawness and permanence, protection, and perhaps a bit of escapism.\
Metalwork, ornate detailing that evokes calligraphy and scrollwork, jewel tones, and darker woods\'97not to mention technologies borne of antiquity like forging, blacksmithing, and tin plating\'97are some prominent themes.\'a0Elsewhere, across fashion (look to the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.instagram.com/p/Cl6b6Kvyhda/?hl=en"}}{\fldrslt \ul knit armored offerings from Isa Boulder}},\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.instagram.com/p/CkLAN-qK0NF/?hl=en"}}{\fldrslt \ul boned corsets from KNWLS}}, and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.instagram.com/p/ClB_DfMMsmL/?hl=en"}}{\fldrslt \ul Paloma Wool\'92s ode to Joan of Arc}}) and jewelry (indie creators like\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://floatingworld.shop/"}}{\fldrslt \ul Floating World}},\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://gracefforde.com/"}}{\fldrslt \ul Grace Fforde}}, and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.clarkstudiojewelry.com/shop"}}{\fldrslt \ul CLARK}}), the mood is absolutely exuding Ren Faire realness.\
\
[\'85] Frank Traynor, the artist behind\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.instagram.com/theperfectnothingcatalog/"}}{\fldrslt \ul The Perfect Nothing Catalog}}, has developed a unique style of gem-encrusted tin-over-copper lattice work that transforms quotidian objects\'97lightswitch plates, bath faucets, and even trash cans and pepper mills\'97into relics of uncommon charm. Using collected shells, stones, and other glittering bits, the result is a Buried Treasure meets Met Cloisters meets\'a0
\f3\i Grimms\'92 Fairy Tales
\f2\i0 \'a0mashup. But for the New York\'96based designer\'a0Sophie Lou Jacobsen, whose wavy and colorful glassware can be spotted all over Instagram, the recent pivot toward silver and embroidered pieces articulates a new, or rather\'a0old, array of influences. \'93Personally, I\'92ve been feeling very drawn to Old World aesthetics,\'94 she explains in an email. \'93Rich colors, texture, layers, lots of ornamentation and decoration\'85astronomy and botany.\'94 \
\
[\'85]\
\
The furniture dealer Bianca Stillwell of\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.instagram.com/monte.vision/"}}{\fldrslt \ul Monte Visi\'f3n}}\'a0has been a bellwether of this vibe shift.\'a0\'93I\'92ve never been into Scandinavian, really, so I\'92m particularly excited to see this darker stuff creeping in,\'94 she says. \'93These days I am more into esoteric-leaning, darker, moodier colors and furniture. I really care about seeing a human touch to stuff. I love stone, I love steel, I love wood, I love Old World craft.\'94\'a0Whereas Scandinavian aesthetics are decidedly muted and light-of-touch, and postmodernism feels optimistic if a bit unhinged, medieval aesthetics are enveloping, immersive, and transporting. As we have reentered the world following a season of forced isolation, many of us have found our circumstances to be less than hospitable.\'a0\
\'93I associate medieval times with the tension between poverty and extreme wealth exacerbated by plagues, which created an overarching sense of darkness and helplessness,\'94 Sophie notes. \'93But when you look at the aesthetics and artifacts of that time they are often full of whimsy and fantasy.\'94\
[\'85]\
For Chase Biado and Antonia Pinter of\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://a-history-of-frogs.com/"}}{\fldrslt \ul A History of Frogs}}, the element of fantasy is inextricable from their artistic vision. \'93We are deeply invested in the role fantasy plays in our daily lives, [and] we like to play with the past.\'94\'a0\
\
Their creations\'97most recently, an\'a0assemblage\'a0of bronze, brass, copper, and patinated aluminum sculptures and objects that are at turns lace-y, drip-castle-y, a bit primitive yet otherworldly\'97defy direct allegiance to a particular historical context. A History of Frogs has used evocative terms like Goblin Baroque and Marsupial Gothic that gesture toward, but ultimately reach beyond, a known history. They describe their work as \'93anti-modernism\'94 because it\'92s ornate and decorative, but also imperfect and idiosyncratic.\
But the draw to fantasy is more than a stylistic interest. \'93Our love of fantasy comes in part from a dissatisfaction with the world and a desire for more\'97more magic, more emotion, more imagination,\'94 Chase and Antonia explain. \'93[We] try to bring that into the world through the objects we make.\'94 Their use of metals also echoes a sentiment expressed by the other makers engaging with medieval aesthetics. \'93We have a desire to build something that is going to last a while, when so much seems disposable,\'94 they add.\
[\'85]\
If one thing is clear, it\'92s that medieval is as much a container of human imagination as it is a period of history. It embraces a plurality of longings, tastes, impulses, and inspirations: a \'93dirty-footed ideal\'94 for Traynor, \'93extravagance and beauty\'94 for Carson, a slow and intentional creative physicality untouched by industry for Lane. The Middle Ages Modern aesthetic is both darkness and magical thinking; of the past yet also of our own imagining. Perhaps, after a shared transit through hardship, we\'92re all planting the seeds of a more hopeful renaissance to come.
